WEBVTT

00:08.560 --> 00:12.580
Coming up next is the Science Fiction Radio Show, so stay with us.

00:28.740 --> 00:34.180
This is the Science Fiction Radio Show, a commentary on science fiction and
fantasy.

00:36.920 --> 00:38.660
And here are your hosts.

00:43.380 --> 00:52.700
This is David Crews. And Daryl Lane. If there's such a thing as a science fiction
connoisseur, he would have to be a Jack Vance fan. Vance is a distinctive author

00:52.700 --> 01:01.060
who's been writing science fiction and fantasy since the 1940s. And even in a
field like science fiction, Vance's imagination is remarkable. His depiction of

01:01.060 --> 01:09.000
alien worlds, for instance, impresses any reader. He has a powerful, subtle
style, and with the colors and textures of his descriptions, and his careful

01:09.000 --> 01:16.440
attention to the resources of language, he can make you believe you're on
another planet, somehow involved in an alien culture. We might mention the

01:16.440 --> 01:26.080
Durdane trilogy, or the Four Novels of the Tschai, or Planet of Adventure series,
as examples of Vance's skill at creating alien environments and cultures. Vance

01:26.080 --> 01:29.500
always wanted to be a writer, and he chose science fiction for the simplest of
reasons.

01:30.900 --> 01:34.240
First, I had a quite the ideal of my life.

01:35.960 --> 01:42.200
I wanted to find some way of making a living where I could travel, be my own boss,

01:42.660 --> 01:52.140
work my own hours, and writing was the way that suggested itself.

01:53.700 --> 02:03.840
And so I kind of, even when I was only 10 or 12 years old,

02:04.500 --> 02:09.720
Well, I told myself I kind of liked to be
a writer, but I chose science fiction. I don't know, or fantasy, whatever you

02:09.720 --> 02:17.220
want to call it. When I was a kid, I'd done a lot of reading. Well, I'd done a
lot of reading in everything as far as I could.

02:21.000 --> 02:38.960
but I think I'm probably more touched by, or not influenced by the word, but
influenced, I guess you might say, by the fantasy and the so-called science

02:38.960 --> 02:49.340
fiction, rather than by much anything else. As we've said, Vance started back in
the 1940s in the pulp magazines, and his early work lacks the polish and

02:49.340 --> 03:01.500
distinctive flair that he's known for. I was learning my trade. I just got
started writing not as real young, you know, like some guys did. In fact, I was

03:01.500 --> 03:13.180
doing lots of other things. And then I decided I was going to be a writer, and I
started writing, and I had all the talents for it, I guess, apparently, but I

03:13.180 --> 03:25.000
didn't have the knack or the practice, or whatever you want to call it, of
putting the words together. And also, I was trying

03:25.000 --> 03:37.820
to write the wrong kind of story. Those days, the gadget story was very big. And
I was wasting a lot of time trying to write gadget stories on scientific

03:37.820 --> 03:56.500
breakthroughs and things like that, which is essentially kind of a lined alley,
I think. And it's a phase of the field which has mercifully gone over the hill.

03:57.300 --> 04:10.300
I've got a very good scientific background. It's not that I don't know science.
I do write. I was going to be a physicist, actually, for a while. In the 40s and

04:10.300 --> 04:27.420
50s, I was writing and experimenting, collecting rejection slips. And that was
an apprentice period in which I

04:27.420 --> 04:42.480
was paid not very much for, but, you know, checked once in a while. Essentially,
those 40s and 50s stories are not much good. They're not worth it. I'll just soon

04:42.480 --> 04:52.320
forget them. Vance's apprenticeship must have been well spent. The science
fiction and fantasy he's been writing ever since is masterful. In 1963, he won

04:52.320 --> 05:01.520
the Hugo Award for The Dragon Masters. And in 1966, he won both the Nebula and
Hugo Awards for The Last Castle. Tomorrow, more with Jack Vance.

05:09.280 --> 05:17.280
This has been the Science Fiction Radio Show, a production of the Permian Basin
Science Fiction Association, produced in conjunction with Odessa College in

05:17.280 --> 05:18.060
Odessa, Texas.

