06:26.260 --> 06:27.780
And here are your hosts.

06:32.680 --> 06:41.720
This is Daryl Lane and David Crews. Jack Vance has created a unique, vivid, and
fascinating body of science fiction and fantasy. He began his career in the pulp

06:41.720 --> 06:49.480
magazines of the 1940s, and he wrote the gadget stories that were popular then.
But over the years, he's developed a deeper, more subtle, and distinctive type

06:49.480 --> 06:57.500
of science fiction and fantasy. Yet the curious fact is that not many people,
even science fiction readers, have heard of Jack Vance. We asked him why he

06:57.500 --> 07:13.560
thought that was so. I think another thing, too, that I've developed rather
gradually and reached my presence, whatever you want to call it, by a kind of

07:13.560 --> 07:21.180
back way, inconspicuously. Clark is known for it in 2001.

07:23.480 --> 07:29.360
Heinlein, Stranger in a Strange Land, or whatever, children's books, or through
Campbell.

07:33.560 --> 07:35.360
And it's, uh...

07:40.060 --> 07:53.000
I've never been associated with anything that had any other publicity attached
to it. So that I just seemed to arrive on the scene. So it seems to me, if I

07:53.000 --> 08:08.500
were looking at my own career in this way, and then kind of quietly from, from,
uh, northeast somewhere. Rather than, uh, through, through having a movie or, or

08:08.500 --> 08:18.480
something or so. Lately, Vance has been writing three, four, and even five novel
series set on alien planets. He's noted for his imaginative descriptions of

08:18.480 --> 08:26.520
alien settings and cultures more than anything else. The four books in the Tschai
series, or the Durdane trilogy, are good examples of stories set in convincingly

08:26.520 --> 08:34.920
alien environments. Vance is also recognized for the stories in the Dying Earth
series. And don't forget, Vance has written excellent mystery fiction, even

08:34.920 --> 08:43.600
winning the Edgar Award from the Mystery Writers of America in 1960, for his
book, The Man in the Cage. Even though some readers talk of a unique Vance

08:43.600 --> 08:55.660
style, Vance himself says he has no particular style or writing characteristics.
I don't have any style. All I do is try to write whatever in the best possible

08:55.660 --> 09:08.340
way. Now, if, uh, you take the trouble to read, uh, some of my murder mysteries,
you'll find that they're, they're written in a different way. Everything you

09:08.340 --> 09:20.200
write, everything I write, everything anybody writes, the style, or the way the
words are put together, is part of the mood of the story. It, uh, it is part of

09:20.200 --> 09:32.120
the story itself. It's part of the complete, completed product. Now, when you
say, uh, why did I, how did I evolve this? That, that, that implies that I have

09:32.120 --> 09:49.940
one style that I use for everything from, uh, this, uh, early Dying Earth thing,
up to, uh, one of, well, this mystery story, uh, with locale in the countryside

09:49.940 --> 09:59.180
out here, called Fox Valley Murders. If you take the trouble to examine the way
the words are put together, you'll find it totally different. Also, like, is Bad

09:59.180 --> 10:09.760
Ronald, which is a suspense story. The way that the words go together are
different from the way the words go together, and you say, uh, oh, I don't know

10:09.760 --> 10:13.760
what. No, I don't have any style. 

10:19.800 --> 10:28.720
Vance considers himself a storyteller or entertainer, with no access to
grind. He's reluctant to provide explanations or analyses of his work. When

10:28.720 --> 10:37.260
asked about a particular character or episode in one of his works, Vance has a
characteristic reply. Well, I think everyone will have to answer that to

10:37.260 --> 10:45.220
themselves. Reading the science fiction of Jack Vance makes answering questions
like that worthwhile. More with Jack Vance tomorrow.

