12:15.940 --> 12:25.080
This is David Crews. And Daryl Lane. The Dying Earth stories of Jack Vance, one
of the most exquisite creations in the realm of science fantasy. The setting for

12:25.080 --> 12:33.820
the stories is a bit unusual. It's Earth, but an Earth so many millions of
centuries into the future that it's almost dead. And so is the sun, sputtering

12:33.820 --> 12:41.840
like a candle ready to go out and bathing Earth in its final pale red light.
There are only a few people left on Earth, and most of these are sorcerers,

12:41.980 --> 12:51.880
since magic works and science has been forgotten. Vance says the dying Earth
stories are some of the earliest things he ever wrote. Well, the funny thing

12:51.880 --> 13:04.260
about it is that was written before I started selling. That was written at sea.
It was merchant sealant. And I had quite a bit of spare time, and I began

13:04.260 --> 13:10.520
writing these flamboyant,

13:10.600 --> 13:27.880
highly colored stories. But those were written, oh, very, very early. They were
written before I started selling. So they're just representative of a kind of

13:27.880 --> 13:31.080
rather early stage.

13:32.400 --> 13:45.140
And then when I started writing this so-called gadget fiction or other stuff, I
changed the style. The style of the Dying Earth stuff wasn't at all suitable for

13:45.140 --> 13:57.980
writing the stuff I began selling. The stuff I was selling was any good, because
it wasn't. But at least the style of the Dying Earth would have been absolutely,

13:58.220 --> 14:02.640
what's

14:02.640 --> 14:07.040
the word, incongruous. It wouldn't have fitted for any different style.

14:18.700 --> 14:26.680
Many readers believe the style of the stories, which Vance calls flamboyant and
highly colored, to be the most marvelous and vivid thing about them. It creates

14:26.680 --> 14:34.560
an exotic yet wistful atmosphere, somehow appropriate for a world on the edge of
extinction. Tim Underwood is a friend of Vance's, and along with Chuck Miller,

14:34.820 --> 14:42.480
publishes Vance's work in specially made collector's editions. The Underwood
Miller Publishing Company's first book was the Dying Earth. We asked Tim

14:42.480 --> 14:57.200
Underwood why. A lot of science fiction and fantasy, and sometimes the best of
it, does not get published in hardcover editions. And the Dying Earth was the

14:57.200 --> 15:11.140
first book we did, and it was just a book that is essentially a classic. It was
published in 1950 as a paperback, and it had never been in hardcover, and it's

15:11.140 --> 15:20.640
one of the outstanding books in the fantasy field, and 200 years from now people
will be reading it. And it had never been in a durable hardcover edition, and so

15:20.640 --> 15:21.420
we put it in one.

15:28.980 --> 15:37.640
Vance didn't write any new Dying Earth material for 15 years after the book's
original publication in 1950. We asked him if it was perhaps reader responses

15:37.640 --> 15:53.160
which caused him to take it up again. No, it's been, I don't, I just, well, we
wanted to do some more stuff in there. And this character was swarming around in

15:53.160 --> 15:53.580
my head.

16:10.680 --> 16:18.700
The character swarming around in his head was Cugel, a picaresque rogue who
survives on the Dying Earth through his wits and his nimble fingers. The Kugel

16:18.700 --> 16:27.320
stories were collected in 1966 in a book entitled The Eyes of the Overworld.
Since then, Vance has written other Cugel stories and says he'll do more in the

16:27.320 --> 16:31.800
future, so the Dying Earth isn't dead yet. More on Jack Vance tomorrow.

