18:02.260 --> 18:10.660
This is Daryl Lane and David Crews. Jack Vance is one of the major talents that
the field of fantasy and science fiction has produced. Tim Underwood, his friend

18:10.660 --> 18:21.940
and publisher, offers some reasons why. I think Jack has accomplished some
things with some of his works that have never been done before. And not only in

18:21.940 --> 18:23.660
terms of style, but in terms of feeling.

18:27.900 --> 18:41.540
He hearkens to a certain spirit, I think. I mean, a certain kind of person or a
certain kind of spirit is on his wavelength and responds strongly to his work.

18:43.240 --> 18:54.040
But the latter part of his work and the best of his work is extremely well
crafted. He's a craftsman, very well written, and accomplishes a lot of really

18:54.040 --> 19:03.460
unusual things in a very quiet way. Vance's accomplishments have been
impressive. His science fiction career spans almost 40 years and began back in

19:03.460 --> 19:11.520
the pulp era. He's won the major awards for a science fiction and fantasy
writer. One is the Hugo Award, awarded by readers, and the other is a Nebula

19:11.520 --> 19:19.520
Award, given by other writers. Some of his best-known work includes The Dying
Earth stories, which go all the way back to his beginnings as a writer in the

19:19.520 --> 19:33.680
40s, and more recently, The Five Demon Princes novels. Still, Vance hasn't
received much recognition. We asked Underwood why. My feeling is that one

19:33.680 --> 19:50.060
responds strongly to Vance, one who feels much the same way about the world that
he does. I think, why isn't he, though, as popular as, say, John Lycoray, who I

19:50.060 --> 20:04.740
think people respond to in the same way? Well, Vance is more of a rarefied
taste, I think, is the kind of things that he feels are important. The

20:04.740 --> 20:16.500
strangeness in the world about us and the unusual qualities of life itself,
those kind of considerations are not important to a lot of people. People who do

20:16.500 --> 20:26.560
feel these things strongly are going to like what Vance writes. They're going to
enjoy reading. They're going to enjoy the worlds that he's created. He's not

20:26.560 --> 20:38.940
done a lot of the things that make other writers successful, like he's never
stayed with one character, the way that, say, Laker Ray stayed with Smiley, or

20:38.940 --> 20:56.500
the way that someone writes a Doc Savage novel 15 times in a row or whatever. He
hasn't done that. And he hasn't had one hero that he's repeated for any great

20:56.500 --> 21:11.480
number of books, and he hasn't had one contemporary theme that appeals to
people, like the battle of the sexes or something like that. Those aren't Jack's

21:11.480 --> 21:23.780
themes. Jack's considerations and themes are enormously subtle and kind of a
rarefied nature. Vance has always been reluctant to discuss his own work or to

21:23.780 --> 21:35.600
offer any insights into his themes or intentions. Underwood suggests a reason.
Jack always says that he wants his work to stand for and by itself. I think he

21:35.600 --> 21:48.580
just wants to be remembered for his work. He refuses to pick favorites among his
work. I know he likes his Demon Prince series a lot for good reason. He likes

21:48.580 --> 22:03.200
The Palace of Love, which is the third in that series. He likes The Eyes of the
Overworld, the sequenced stories of the fellow Kugel. And that's partly because

22:03.200 --> 22:17.860
Kugel's a rascal, and Vance is often a bit of a rascal, and Kugel's even more
so. He's the kind of rascal that Vance would like to be if he wasn't such a nice

22:17.860 --> 22:18.560
guy at heart.

