23:48.320 --> 23:57.340
This is David Crews. And Daryl Lane. In 1975, a science fiction and fantasy
publishing company was formed because two men wanted to get one particular

23:57.340 --> 24:04.360
science fantasy book between hardcovers. Tim Underwood, one of the men,
explains. In 1975,

24:07.060 --> 24:18.180
I decided I wanted to publish a book. Specifically, I wanted to publish The
Dying Earth in a hardcover form. And I was a used book dealer, and Chuck Miller

24:18.180 --> 24:29.520
was a used book dealer, dealing in rare and out-of-print books and some new
material. And we knew of each other. And I think we had bought and sold books

24:29.520 --> 24:41.940
from each other from time to time. And Chuck heard about, I may have mentioned
in a letter about The Dying Earth, and Chuck offered his expertise because he

24:41.940 --> 24:53.580
knew a good deal about certain parts of publishing industry, about distribution
and that end of it. And my experience, my limited experience, had to do with

24:53.580 --> 25:06.300
just graphically putting a book together. And so he suggested that we do the
book together. And so we did. And the interesting thing is that we never met

25:06.300 --> 25:12.580
each other until the book had already been published. And that was a year later
in 1976.

25:15.080 --> 25:27.240
And up to that time, we were literally exchanging thousands of dollars to the
mail and doing business without ever having met each other. We were, in a sense,

25:27.340 --> 25:37.100
complete strangers. But we had this one connection, and that is we both felt
strongly about this one work of Vance's The Dying Earth and about Vance's work

25:37.100 --> 25:47.100
in general and about, specifically about fantasy and science fiction and horror
and literature. Since that first book, the Underwood Miller Company has

25:47.100 --> 25:55.820
published some 50 books, all science fiction, fantasy, and horror. Their print
runs for each volume average 1,000 copies, hardly enough to compete with the

25:55.820 --> 26:06.140
large New York publishers. Underwood explains why. We're selling to collectors,
and the collectors are buying these books with the knowledge that they're going

26:06.140 --> 26:22.520
to go out of print and become valuable later on. Another reason is that Chuck
and I don't own a warehouse, and we are not in business to have a large

26:22.520 --> 26:32.620
inventory. We couldn't. We would make more money if we printed more books,
because as you print more books, the cost per book of manufacturing goes down

26:32.620 --> 26:33.280
dramatically.

26:36.980 --> 26:46.560
But we just simply can't afford to have a lot of books in inventory sitting
around. We can't afford it. Our books go out of print in about nine months, and

26:46.560 --> 26:57.000
this is just the opposite of a major manufacturer, like Dutton or Brown or
someone like that. They want their book to stay in print as long as possible,

26:57.580 --> 27:00.580
and we want our books to go out of print as soon as possible.

27:08.100 --> 27:16.980
Tim Underwood and Chuck Miller have a sincere interest in significant works of
science fiction and fantasy. It's just the pleasure of bookmaking. Just the

27:16.980 --> 27:28.660
pleasure. Chuck and I both take a great pleasure in making a good book, a book
that has its signature sewn, which is something that doesn't occur in general

27:28.660 --> 27:39.960
trade hardcover publishing anymore, a book that's printed on acid-free paper so
that in 20 or 30 years the paper won't turn brittle and brown, and just a well

27:39.960 --> 27:50.200
-made, well-bound book, attractively made and artistically put together. And
publishing a book like that, creating a book like that, is really a pleasure.

27:51.540 --> 27:58.600
Underwood and Miller are publishing books by many authors in beautifully
illustrated editions now. Anyone who likes fantasy and science fiction, and

27:58.600 --> 28:02.140
anyone who likes books, should search out some of their work and hold on to it.

